<Section title = "The capsizing ship" id = "capsizing_ship"></Section>
    
<SubSection title = "Background" id = "background">

<p>
    We are all familiar with the notion of the center of mass of a rigid body. In class, we have described the 
    position of the center of mass to be the average position of all the constitutent mass elements 
    weighted by the the total mass of the body. We have also learnt how to find the center of mass of composite bodies 
    and derived simple expressions for basic shapes. This practice can sometimes seem abstract, but do you know that 
    center of mass calculations are integral in understanding the stability of dynamic structures? 
</p>

    <Image alt = "Capsized ship" src = "/dyn/Capsized_ship.jpg" width = 7>

    <p class = "figureCaption">
        The MV Golden Ray <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" 
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MV_Golden_Ray">capsized
        </a> on 8 September 2019 in 
        St. Simons Sound near the Port of Brunswick in Georgia, United States. 
        Image Source: U.S. Coast Guard District 7 PADE. 
    </p>
    </Image>

    <p>
        The MV Golden Ray, a 656-foot long roll-on/roll-off vehicle carrier, collapsed on 
        8 September 2019 in between the Colonel's Island Terminal in the Port of Brunswick, Georgia, 
        and Baltimore, Maryland. You can read more about the incident 
        <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" 
        href="https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/14/us/golden-ray-cargo-ship-ntsb-report/index.html">here.</a> 
        After thorough investigations by the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB), 
        it was found that the chief officer of the ship entered erroneous ballast quantities into the stability 
        calculation program, which produced incorrect stability conditions of the ship. In other words, a 
        moment or torque was generated from the difference between 
        the locations of the center of mass and the center of buoyancy.
        This torque arm produced an angular acceleration &alpha; that was opposite to the angular displacement
        &theta;, which meant that the ship was in unstable equilibrium. Thus, the failure in accounting for the 
        changes in ballast quantities meant that the hull of the ship was unable to provide a counter torque to
        these forces, and the ship capsized. Observe how you can combine concepts from both
        TAM 210/211 and TAM 212!
    </p>

